    <section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00010"><title>Learning Outcomes</title>
      <para id="para-00001">By the end of this section, you will be able to:</para>
      <list id="list-00001">
        <item>Demonstrate self-awareness in attitudes, beliefs, and values.</item>
        <item>Identify personal biases and stereotypes.</item>
        <item>Identify strategies to overcome barriers to cultural competence.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <para id="para-00002">Numerous factors can affect the process of providing culturally competent care. Personal factors of the nurse, including their value system, beliefs, and customs, as well as the nurse’s knowledge and attitudes about other cultures, play a role. Cultural factors such as language and communication barriers, gendered roles, and health care practices readily impact the interactions between nurses and clients. Nurses with limited experience interacting with clients from different backgrounds may exhibit biases, othering, and stereotyping in their approach to care.</para>
    <section id="sect-00001">
      <title>Personal Factors</title>
      <para id="para-00003">An individual’s experiences, cultural background, attitudes, age, and educational preparation are all factors that can affect cultural competence. Younger generations are increasingly more diverse (Pew Research Center, 2018), and older individuals may be less familiar with changing cultural dynamics. Education is also an important factor as it can provide individuals with the knowledge, skills, and critical thinking tools to effectively interact with people from diverse backgrounds. Individuals educated in a diverse environment and with some cross-cultural knowledge may be more adept at interactions with people outside their own culture (Sharifi, 2019). Socialization, personality, and prior experiences also play a role, as people who were raised in diverse communities or have experience traveling may feel more comfortable interacting with people from different cultures in a variety of settings, such as in the workplace, in social situations, and in their community.</para>
    <section id="sect-00002">
      <title>Biases and Stereotyping</title>
      <para id="para-00004"><term id="term-00001">Biases</term> are prejudicial attitudes or preconceptions that act as filters to the way people perceive, interpret, and react to the world. These opinions or beliefs (involving gender, race, age, or other categories) affect decision making in subtle and overt ways. When nurses focus only on certain information while ignoring other relevant data, biases can lead to incorrect assumptions, judgments, and actions. In health care, biases can cause health care workers to draw false conclusions, lead to disparities in diagnoses and treatments, result in unequal access to services and resources, and result in slower response times for individuals belonging to certain groups, such as people of color, those who identify as <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00002">LGBTQ+</term>, and people belonging to different religions. Finally, biases can lead nurses to ignore their own prejudices, resulting in a lack of cultural sensitivity and respect.</para>
      <para id="para-00005"><term id="term-00003">Stereotyping</term> is the act of ascribing certain characteristics or behaviors to a person based on their membership in a particular group. This can involve making assumptions about people based on their perceived race, ethnicity, religion, gender identity, age, socioeconomic status, ability, or sexual orientation. Stereotyping can lead to assumptions and generalizations about individuals and groups that may not be accurate or fair. In health care, stereotyping can have a negative impact if it leads to unequal, inadequate, or inappropriate client care. Stereotyping can also prevent health care providers from effectively communicating with and understanding the needs of their clients, which can negatively impact the quality of care that clients receive. To guard against the harmful effects of stereotyping, nurses must gather and utilize accurate information about their clients as individuals, rather than relying on learned, and potentially damaging, assumptions.</para>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00003">
      <title>Othering</title>
      <para id="para-00006"><term id="term-00004">Othering</term> is the process of excluding, marginalizing, or differentiating individuals or groups based on their perceived differences from the dominant group in a society. Othering is used to separate or exclude individuals who may not fit within social norms or expectations. It often involves ascribing negative characteristics or traits to individuals or groups based on their perceived differences, implying that a person or group are inferior. This can lead to discrimination, feelings of isolation, and social inequality. Othering can take many forms, such as <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00005">racism</term>, <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00006">sexism</term>, <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00007">homophobia</term>, <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00008"> ableism</term>, and other varieties of discrimination. The practice of othering can have harmful effects on individuals and communities, as it can create barriers to social inclusion, equal opportunities, and fair treatment. It can also reinforce negative stereotypes and prejudices and can prevent individuals and groups from being treated with dignity and respect.</para>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00004">
      <title>Developing Self-awareness</title>
      <para id="para-00007"><term id="term-00009">Self-awareness</term> is an important step in developing cultural competence and cultural humility (Foronda et al., 2018). It involves understanding one’s own values and beliefs, how they are influenced by one’s cultural background, and how they influence one’s perceptions and behaviors. To develop self-awareness, nurses can start by reflecting on their experiences, cultural background, biases, and stereotypes, and how these may impact their views of people from different backgrounds.</para>
      <para id="para-00008">There are a number of tools and approaches for working toward this self-awareness. One example is the <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00010">Implicit Association Test (IAT)</term>, a psychological tool used to measure bias and the effect that unconscious attitudes and beliefs have on day-to-day decision making. People of any background can use the IAT to identify hidden biases that may affect their objective evaluation and treatment of others. Once biases are identified, nurses can challenge their biases by engaging in open and respectful conversations with individuals from different backgrounds and asking those individuals questions to learn more about their experiences and perspectives.</para>
      <para id="para-00009">Participating in organizations that embrace and promote diversity can also help nurses develop self-awareness and cultural competence. Examples of such activities may include attending cultural events, volunteering at health clinics that serve immigrant communities, or attending an interfaith service. By engaging in these activities, nurses can continue to learn and grow in their understanding of working with individuals and groups from diverse cultural backgrounds, building the skills and knowledge necessary to provide compassionate, culturally congruent care to their clients.</para>
      <para id="para-00010">The <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00011">Colorado Education Initiative</term> has developed a Cultural Competence Self-Awareness Checklist that individuals  can use to check their progress toward developing cultural competence.</para>

