    <section id="sect-00005">
      <title>Barriers to Providing Culturally Competenet Care</title>
      <para id="para-00014">Nurses face multiple barriers to providing culturally competent care. They often lack knowledge of different cultural norms and values, face language and communication barriers, and resort to stereotyping due to lack of cultural awareness and limited cultural diversity among health care providers. These challenges can lead to misunderstandings and misdiagnoses, as well as poor client outcomes. In addition, ethnocentrism, <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00012">gendered roles</term>, <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00013">organizational barriers</term>, and <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00014">structural inequities</term> present challenges.</para>
      <section id="sect-00006">
        <title>Ethnocentrism</title>
        <para id="para-00015"><term id="term-00015">Ethnocentrism</term> is the belief that one's own cultural values, traditions, and practices are superior to those of other cultures (Bizumic &amp; Duckitt, 2012). Ethnocentrism involves judging others by the standards of one’s own culture, assuming that one’s own culture is the norm, or standard, against which all others should be measured. Ethnocentrism can lead to a lack of understanding and respect for other cultures and can result in discrimination, <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00016">bias</term>, and even violence. Nurses need to be aware of their own ethnocentric tendencies, striving to be more culturally aware and culturally sensitive. Practicing cultural humility allows one to recognize the biases created by ethnocentrism, emphasizing the client’s values, rather than those of the nurse or the dominant culture ((Foronda &amp; Baptiste, 2022).</para>
      </section>
      <section id="sect-00007">
        <title>Gendered Roles</title>
        <para id="para-00016"><term id="term-00017">Gender roles</term> and expectations can have a major impact on how individuals from various cultures seek and respond to care. Nursing is often viewed as a gendered role because it has traditionally been associated with women. This gendered association can affect the way that the profession is perceived and valued and can impact interactions between nurses and clients. Nurses should recognize that people of different genders may have varying needs and expectations when it comes to health care. For example, individuals from some cultures may require separate rooms for male and female clients or may prefer that a nurse of the same gender as the client provides care. Understanding how gender and gender roles are viewed from different cultural perspectives can help nurses recognize how gender impacts decision-making, health beliefs, and behaviors of clients when it comes to seeking health care.</para>
      </section>
      <section id="sect-00008">
        <title>Organizational Barriers</title>
        <para id="para-00017">Barriers to cultural competence also occur within organizations. These barriers can be far-reaching in scope as they extend well beyond the individual. Factors such as staff education, diversity among health care providers, policies and procedures for addressing cultural differences, and access to language services can all impact the ability of nurses to provide culturally congruent care. Organizational leadership plays a key role in designing and implementing policies that support an inclusive workplace and the provision of culturally and <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00018">linguistically competent services</term> (Office of Minority Health, 2013). Furthermore, since cultural competence is a process, there must be a commitment to updating and maintaining programs and policies that support it.</para>
      </section>
      <section id="sect-00009">
        <title>Structural Inequities</title>
        <para id="para-00018"><term id="term-00019">Structural inequities</term> in health care refer to the systemic barriers and disparities that exist in the health care system that prevent certain individuals or groups from receiving high-quality care. These inequities can be caused by a range of factors, including discriminatory policies and practices, unequal access to health care resources, and inadequate representation of certain groups in the health care workforce.</para>
        <para id="para-00019">One example of a structural inequity in health care is the unequal distribution of health care resources, such as diagnostic and treatment facilities, across different communities. For example, individuals in rural areas or those living in communities of lower socioeconomic status may have limited access to specialized medical care. This lack of access to care can have a significant impact on population health, as it can result in individuals not receiving the care they need, leading to an increase in preventable illnesses and chronic conditions and disparities in health outcomes, with individuals living in under-served areas often experiencing worse health outcomes than those living in more affluent areas.</para>
        <para id="para-00020">Another example of a structural inequity in health care is the lack of representation of certain groups in the health care workforce. For instance, Black and Latinx individuals are underrepresented in the medical nursing professions, which can lead to a lack of cultural competency and culturally congruent care for clients from these backgrounds and a reduction in the quality of care provided.</para>
      </section>
